is important.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>Think carefully about the limitations of straightforward methods and how you should adjust your approach to overcome these.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>Don’t mix up the success metrics for your project vs the policy</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>For problem 1: </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" err="1"/><a:t>Operationalising</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t> the “good” school concept is difficult, pay more attention to how you can do that thoughtfully</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>For problem 2: Think carefully about whether how “aligned” a course is to a job is all there is to how valuable a course / degree is</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp></p:spTree><p:extLst><p:ext uri="{BB962C8B-B14F-4D97-AF65-F5344CB8AC3E}"><p14:creationId xmlns:p14="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2010/main" val="585588003"/></p:ext></p:extLst></p:cSld><p:clrMapOvr><a:masterClrMapping/></p:clrMapOvr></p:sld>